    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. What are some of the common criticisms or alternative legal arguments people have regarding that interpretation of due process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics of substantive due process argue that it allows unelected judges to make decisions that should be left to the democratic process. They believe it undermines the principle of majority rule and can lead to judicial activism, where judges impose their personal values on society. Additionally, some argue that it stretches the original intent of the Constitution, which they believe was meant to protect procedural fairness, not to guarantee specific rights. Instead, they advocate for a more literal interpretation of the Constitution, emphasizing that rights should be explicitly stated or derived from the text. This perspective contends that substantive due process can lead to judicial overreach and a lack of accountability, as judges are not directly answerable to the electorate.",
      "source": "target",
